[49m[39m  401, 401[0m:[39m[49m - Patients awaiting specific procedures with unpredictable scheduling (e.g., OR availability)
[0m[49m[39m  402, 402[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  403, 403[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  404, 404[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pseudocode and architecture above give you the shape of the solution. Here's what's missing before you'd trust it with real bed management decisions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No model governance workflow.** Production needs a formal model approval pipeline: automated evaluation against a holdout set, comparison to the currently deployed model, bias/fairness checks across demographic strata, and a human sign-off gate before any model reaches a live endpoint. The Model Registry's PendingManualApproval status is a starting point, but you also need documented acceptance criteria and a rollback procedure if a new model underperforms in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No integration testing against the EHR feed.** The pipeline assumes clean FHIR data from HealthLake. Real EHR feeds have schema variations, missing fields, delayed events, and duplicate messages. You need integration tests that simulate malformed ADT events, out-of-order lab results, and HealthLake API throttling. Without them, the first production hiccup becomes a silent accuracy degradation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No error handling or dead-letter paths.** Every Lambda invocation, every Feature Store write, every endpoint call can fail. Production needs: retries with exponential backoff, dead-letter queues for failed predictions, alerting when prediction coverage drops below a threshold (e.g., "only 80% of inpatients have a current prediction"), and graceful degradation when the endpoint is unavailable (fall back to DRG geometric mean as the default prediction).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No social-feature coverage.** The pseudocode shows clinical and admission features but omits the social/disposition features that drive the hardest-to-predict stays. Integrating social work assessments, disposition status, prior authorization timelines, and housing instability flags requires NLP extraction from unstructured notes or dedicated structured data capture workflows. Without these, the model systematically underpredicts for patients with social barriers to discharge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No A/B testing or shadow-mode deployment.** Before replacing the current discharge planning workflow, run the model in shadow mode: generate predictions alongside existing processes, compare outcomes, and measure whether earlier predictions actually change operational decisions. Deploying directly without this validation risks eroding clinician trust if the model's errors are visible before its successes are.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No automated retraining trigger.** The monitoring function detects drift, but nothing automatically kicks off a retraining pipeline when performance degrades. Production needs a closed loop: drift detected, retraining triggered, new model evaluated, approval gate, deployment. Manual retraining doesn't scale when you're maintaining separate models per service line.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  405, 423[0m:[39m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
